The pathology report indicates that the patient has a moderately differentiated rectal carcinoma (G2) that has infiltrated the muscularis (pT2). This means that the cancer has grown into the muscle layer of the rectum but has not gone through it. The report also mentions lymphovascular invasion (L1) and perineural invasion (V1), which suggest that the cancer has spread into the lymphatic vessels and nerves. However, the tumor was completely excised with fine resection margins, meaning that the surgery was successful in removing the entire tumor. Additionally, the lymph nodes were free of cancer (pNO), which is a good prognostic sign.

The American Joint Committee on Cancer (AJCC) TNM staging system is commonly used to stage rectal cancer. Based on the information provided in the pathology report, the patient's TNM stage would be T2N0M0. According to the National Cancer Institute, the 5-year relative survival rate for patients with stage II rectal cancer (which includes T2N0M0) is about 60-80%. Since the patient has undergone complete resection of the tumor and has no lymph node involvement, their prognosis may be better than average. Therefore, it is reasonable to expect that the patient will survive after 2.1 years. However, it is important to note that individual outcomes can vary based on other factors such as the patient's overall health, response to treatment, and any complications that may arise.
